.nh
.TH "SYMAIRA" "1" "May 2026" "Symaira Vault" "OpenPass Manual"

.SH NAME
symaira-device-add - Add this device to an existing multi-device vault


.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBsymaira device add [flags]\fP


.SH DESCRIPTION
Add this device to an existing multi-device vault using a pairing
token and public key obtained via QR code from the original device.

.PP
This command is used on the second device after the initial setup wizard
shows a QR code. It creates a new local vault with its own identity,
adds the first device's public key as a recipient, and saves a pairing
request so the first device can accept it.


.SH OPTIONS
\fB-h\fP, \fB--help\fP[=false]
	help for add

.PP
\fB--name\fP=""
	Name for this device (defaults to hostname)

.PP
\fB--pair\fP[=false]
	Pair with an existing device using QR data


.SH OPTIONS INHERITED FROM PARENT COMMANDS
\fB--color\fP="auto"
	When to emit ANSI color: auto, always, never

.PP
\fB--no-pipe-warning\fP[=false]
	suppress 'reading from non-TTY' warning when piping secrets

.PP
\fB--output\fP="text"
	Output format (text, json, yaml)

.PP
\fB--profile\fP=""
	use a named vault profile

.PP
\fB--quiet\fP[=false]
	suppress non-error output

.PP
\fB--theme\fP=""
	Color preset: default, highcontrast, colorblind (or OPENPASS_THEME)

.PP
\fB--vault\fP="~/.openpass"
	path to the password vault


.SH EXAMPLE
.EX
  openpass device add --pair "123456:age1..."
.EE


.SH SEE ALSO
\fBsymaira-device(1)\fP
